 J. Long, 2t.p.\nGOOD SEASONED WOOD\u2014 For\nSale, cut from greSn timber, and\nwell seasoned. $1.50 and $2.50 per\ncord.' Inquire News office. \u20143t.p.\nFOR SALE\u2014 Good soft, coal heat\ner, cheap, or will exchange for la\nbor. \u2014Burt Snyder.\nRussell H. Young, 24, vuicanizer\nToledo, and Thelma H. Frey, 18,\nWeston.\nGeorge Couture, 36, mechanic,\nSylvania, and Dorothy Spencer, 26,\nBowling Green.\nMyron Rosenbaum, 42 columbi^\nand Inez Miller, 29, Bowling Q.\nRichard Combs, 28, brakeman,\nBowling Green, and Marhta ~Grue\nttjr, 25, seamstress. Bowling Green.\nHerbert Lincoln, 22, painter, of\nToledo, and Irene Kachenmeister,\n21, clerk, Rossford.\nGordon H. Meek; 21, student,\nToledo, and Thelma Gillooly, 21,\nmusic teacher, Grand Rapids. I\nHarry Holbrook, 22, salesman,\nElmore, and Irene Wise,^22, Bowl\ning Green.\nE. W- Dennis, 48, car repairer,\nToledo, and, Ruh Burkett, 27, Per\nry sburg. j\nFrank. Ruswinkie, 26, farmer, of\nPemberville, and Freida Rifle, 20,\nPemberville. i\nM3t3v3t3l3*3*3l3t3t3f3*3t3t3M3*3*3t3t3t3C3M3l\nli. tf. -\u201cCAT MtNTER\nDEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE for\nV TREASURER\nV..'* OF WOOD C\u2019QI NTV\n\u201cGive The Court House\nDuck to The Taxpayers\u2019*\n^cte\u00abcK^c\u00abc\u00abc\u00abcac\u00abctcac\u00abe\u00abc<e9c\u00abe\u00abc\u00ab*e\u00abc\u00abctc\u00abc\u00abe\nMr. Menter, at present, is the\ncashier of The Farmers\u2019 Savings\nBank, at Stony Kidge. Alsa has\nworked for the Citizens\u2019 Savings\nBank, ct-Pemberville.\nHe is a resident of Pemberville,\nwhere he 'was born, and graduated\nfrom Pemberville high school.\nHeld the position of Corporation\nClerk, at Pemberville for two yrs.\n(Refused a second term.)\nMember of'the Pemberville Ex\nchange Cl.nb, and Bethlehem's Ev.\nl.ulheran Church.\nHis hank, at Stony Ridge has\nbeen held up by robbers on two\ndifferent occasions. On their sec\nond yisit, \u201cCap\u201d .had the nerve to\nshoot one of the men, who_was la\nter captured in a hospital in Ken\ntucky. The robber is now serving\na sentence Tit the Ohio penitentiary\nMr. Menter will make a good\nman, for the office he seeks.\n(Sighed) Committee.\nP. S-\u2014It has been 25 years\nsince Pemberville or Northeastern\nWood County lias had a representa\ntivg in the Court House. We will\nleave it to the voters to decide\nwhether we are entitled to one\nthis year or not. THINK!\nKte*eaeie*ieieKie\u00abcieK\u00abete\u00abe^^\ni\nJflSfrRoom Suites\nx In Attractive Oak and Walnut\nI\nI....\nK GRAND RAPIDS, OHIO\n&OOOOUOCCCOCOO\nBefore you purchase your dining\nroom furniture, you should in\nspect these suites of oak and wal\nnut, including table, buffet, and\nsix chairs.Note the distinct\nive quality of the beautiful suite,\nnow on display in our show win\ndow.\nFRED GILL\u2019S FURNITURE\n$Tht Cia-Zel\nBowling Green, Ohio\n'THURSDAY and FRIDAY*\nif\nI\n\"QUEEN HIGH\"\nA new Paramount Picture\nWith lots of laughs\nAn all-star cast\n\nSATURDAY, OPEX 2sl5\nAdmission, 5c and 23c, un.\ntil 0:30\nWARNER BAXTER in\n8\n8\n\n\n\"THE AHZ\u00ab Mb\u2019\nA thrilling o itdoor drama\nThat action-drama fans en\njoy. Alsa Comedy Cartoons\nRIN-TIN-TIN\ns\nid\nSUNDAY and MONDAY,\nOpen 2:15 Sunday\nDANCING SWEETIES\u201d\nlg with SUE CARROL and\nGRANT WITHERS\nL# Hear them Sing\n8\n\u2018\u2018THE KISS WALTZ\u201d V\nX Hundreds of laughs and\nfjf heart throbs too. V\nootsS\nasGooxsooi'\nJolin Delncla, 25, engineer, To\nledo, and Rosaline ICralik, 21, of\nHowling Green.\nPaul J3. Crawford, 23, salesman,\nToledo, and Dorothy A. Sehwandt,\n21, stenographer, Perrysburg.\nNicholas .Drue, 28, letter carrier\nToledo, and Vivian Ramsey, 22,\nBowling Green.\nGabriel Dominique-,. .'8, farmer,\nBairdsown, and Ada Kistler, 18,\nfactory worker, Bairdsown.\nJanies Clark, 21, car washer, of\nBowling Green, and Virginia King\n1(5, Bowling Green.\nProbate Court News\nHearing of land sale in case of\nW. H. Schwan, executor vs Minnie\nWagoner, et al, order of appraise\nment issued.\nFirst partial account filed by O.\nShroyer, guardian of Carrie M;\nStacy.\nInheritance tax in estate of Fred\nHoltmyers, and Sarah A. Stearns,\ncertified to auditor.\nApplication for appointment of\nadministrator of estate of F. W.\nHastings, dismissed and cosis paid.\nFifth partial account j' by M.\nConnor, executor of the will of S.\nB, Albertson.\nInheritance tax in estate of Geo.\nT. Taft, certified to auditor.\nReport \"of sale ol real estate, fi\nled in case of Kathryn M. Grover,\nvs Bernice Wheeler, et al.\nWill of Clara F. Wygant, admit\nted to probate; election of widow\ner, Martin J. Wygant to take un\nder will. Inheritance tax determin\ned amount to be paid, $12.50.\nFourth partial account filed by\nJames M. Diley, guardian of Eloise\nDiley, et al.\nInventory filed by Doris Dayman\nguardian of Carl Dayman; person\nal property, $1.000..\nInheritance tax in'estate of Cora\nV. Spencer, determined. no tax\ndue. Final account, filed by Anna\nShallower, administratrix, with the\nwill annexed.\nLois VanBuren appointed admin\nistratrix of estate of Stephen Van\nBnren.\nNqveda Snyder, appointed admin\nistratrix of estate of James Snyder\nElla Cook appointed administra\ntrix of estate of Catherine M. Cook\nInventory and appraisement fll- I\ned by Frank W. Haskell, asignee oi\nWard E. Smith; personal property\n$4,094; real estate, $5,000.\ncommon nous entries\nJohn L. Greene, vs Cameron Co.\nfinding for defendant, petition. dis\nmissed at plaintiff's costs and no\ntice of appeal filed; bond $100.\nDaisey B. Brandvold vs Thomas\nIS. Fitzgerald, Lillian K- Roper\nmade party defendant with leave\nto answer by November 1, in three\ncauses.\nVloiette Capelle vs Fred capelle\nformer decree vacated, petition dis\nmissed by plaintiff at her costs.\nMary E. Lamb vs clarence G.\nMartin, defendant given leave to\nanswer by October 25.\nJ. E. Kelly, vs Wm. Gonyer,\njudgement for plaintiff $155.11.\nLloyd E. Lashaway vs Carl p.\nAvery, judgement for plaintiff,\n$300.\nGordon Lumber Co., vs Andrew\nGnersoo, judgement for parties.\nCitizens Banking Co., vs Steel\nWool Products, settled, case of the\nsame parties, settled at plaintiff\u2019s\ncost.\nDonald Byington vs George Bec\nker, settled; case dismissed.\nJames B. Hathaway vs Lincoln\nMiller, et al, defendant given leave\nto answer instanter.\nIn matter of-guardianship of G.\nA. Bair, orders of probate court\naffirmed.\nPLUMBING, HEATING\nand SPOUTING\nall kinds of pimps\nA SPECIALTY\n:\u2014PRICES REASONABLE\u2014:\nALL WORK GUARANTEED\nPhone 528 or see\nE. Walters\nGrand Rapids, Ohio\nCitizens Banking Co., 'of Perrys\nburg, vs Loren Hum, et al, defend\nant J. W. Greene Co., given leave\nto file answer and cross-petition in\nstanter.\nJ. W- Greene Co., vs Anna Pro\nnozlnk, plaintiff given leave to file\npetition instanter.\nNew Cases\nThe State of Ohio, ex rel. O. C.\nGray, supt., of banks, in charge of\nthe liquidation of the Commercial\nBank, has brought suit against S.\nS. Canfield in which' he says that\nin November 1928, defendant ex\necuted to the bank a promisor?\nnote for $450 secured by g chattle\nmortgage. Plaintiff says that there\nis due $394.83, on the note and he\nasks judgement for that amount,\nforeclosure of the mortgage and\nsale of the chattle to satisfy jud\ngement.\nThe State of Ohio Ex Rel O- C.\nCray, Supt., of banks in charge Of\nthe liquidation of the Commercial\nBank, has brought suit against E.\nJ. Long as maker and T. O. Whit\nacre, as endorser, and has taken\njudgement for $\u2018589.85 by confes\nsion on a cognovit note.\nThe same plaintiff has brought\nsuit for $206.96 agaihst N. A.\nFreer and T. O- Whitacre. The\nsuit is based on a promisory note\nfor $192, executed by N. A. Freer\nto T. O. Whitacre in September,\n1929, and endorsed by the latter to\nthe Commercial Bank.\nEva Snodgrass has brought suit\nfor divorce against Charles W.\nSnodgrass to whom she was marr\nied in December 1898. She says\nthey have three children, none of\nwhom are minbrs and charges that\nthe defendant has been absent since\n1920. She a3ks that she be grant\ned a divorce and that the defend\nant be barred from dower in and\nproperty she may acquire.\nAssignment of Cases\nJudge E.- G. McClelland Monday\nmade the following assignment of\ncases:\nMonday, October 27, 1930.\n23758\u2014Margaret Stevens vs C.\nGalliher, motion.\n23795\u2014R. D. Bnrrill, vs Lloyd\nElliot, et al, motion.\n23821\u2014Stiger Lumber and Coal\nCo., vs \"Smith Brothers, motion.\n23745\u2014Mary Zabik vs\u2022 Tony Za-\u201d\nbik, motion.\n23760\u2014Edith Wagner vs Ches\nter c. Martin aid of execution.\n23455\u2014dn the \"matter of liquid\nation of Com\u2019l Bank for franchise.\n23590\u2014-CTtneral Utilities Co. vs\nGeorge L\u00bb Metzner motion.\n23706\u2014M. E. Tripp et al, vS.\nLyman E. Robinson, et al, motion.\nTuesday, October 28, 1930.\n23214\u2014M. A. Stahl Florida\nProperties vs .Della E. Gasser, jury\nWednesday, Ocober 29, 1930.\n23476\u2014Annette Bobak vs Edna\nHarter, Jury.\nThursday, October 30, 1930.\n23521\u2014Robert StClair, a minor,\nvs Lon Voland, jury.\nFriday, October 31, 1930\n23521\u2014Hall M. Brough, vs C.\nA. Sheports, et al, court.\nMonday, November 3 1930.\n23535\u2014Carl H. Schwin vs Ab\nraham Loa court.\nTuesday November 4, 1930.\n23544\u2014Myrtle Wilder vs Ray\nmond F. Witte, jury.\nThursday, November 6\n23694\u2014John L. Jacobs vs Will\niam F. Miller, jury.\nFriday, November 7, 1930.\n23549\u2014Herbert G. Harmon vs\nCap Amos, jury.\niwS\nHORSE-SHOEING GENESAI\nBLACKSMITH\nGRAND RAPIDS OHIO\nWelding heavy shafts, our spec\nialty.\nADD WORK guaranteed\nLocated in alley at rear of the\ndrug store.\nATTENTION FARMERS\n\u2014Dead Stock Collection\u2014\nHorses, Cattle, Hogs, Sheep and\nChives removed promptly. Reverse\nphone charges to\nWESTON FERTILIZER CO.\nDay or Night Phone 231. Weston\nKATON\u2019S RESTAURANT\nHe Place to Go for a Good Meal\nSandwiches of all kinds. Regulat\nDinners. Short orders. Ice Cream.\nSundaes, Sodas, Soft Drinks.\nCigars, Cigarettes and Tobaccos.\nWith ^hr Commissioners\nThe County Commissioners, gran\nted the petition of John W. Long\nand others, of Henry twp., for a\nditch. The surveyor is to report on\nFebruary 27.\nTwo ditch improvements in Jack\nson twp., have been granted by the\ncounty Commissioners. They held a\nhearing on the petition of Charles\nStahl, and others for an improve\nment granted it and ordered the\nengineer to make a survey and file\na report by Feb., 23, of next year.\nThe Commissioners held a hear\ning on the petition of Catherine\nWilhelmson, and others for a ditch\nimprovement in Jackson township\nThis improvement was also grant\ned and the engineer ordered to sur\nvey, and file report by Feb. 1931.\n11 YEARS CONSTIPATION,\nGLYCERIN MIX ENDS IT\n\u2018\u2018For 11 years, I tried to get rid\not constipation,\" says Chas. E.\nBlair. \u201cThen at last the simple mix\nture, Adlerika made me regular.\u201d\nThe simple mixture of glyceric,\nbuckthorn bark, saline, etc., (Ad\nlerika) acts on BOTH upper and\nlower bowel, relieving constipation\nin 2 hours! Brings out poisons\nyou never thought were in your\nsystem. Let Adlerika give your\nI stomach and bowels a REAL clean\ni ing, and see how good you feel!\nI \u2014O. P. Hampshire, Druggist\nOhio milk prices, according to\nall indications will remain constant I\nthis fall, in most of the leading\nmarkets and not have their custo\nmary rise.\nFewer cattle are being brought\nto Ohio farms for feeding and fin\nishing this fall than for any sea\nson iu the last twelve.\nMr. and Mrs. Ira Baughman, Mr.\nand Mrs. George Baightel, Mrs. M.\nMiller and Mrs. Mary Geyer, vis\nited Pamy Rebecca Lodge, at Mil\nton, Tuesday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. J. E. Stevens, who\nare in poor health, have gone to\nBowling Green, where they will\nmake their home for the present,\nwith their daughter, Mr. and Mrs.\nChas. Petteys.\nOhio farmers have Invested in\nmachinery $150,000,000 a large\npart of which is lost annually be\ncause of careless storage.\nM\u2019\\ and Mrs. Jas. H. Burwell,\nand Mr., and Mrs. Clarence Free\nworth, spent Sunday in Sycamore,\nat the L. A. Neibel home.\n\u2014CLAUDE L. FILIERE\u2014\nDEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE FOR\nAUDITOR\nOF WOOD COUNTY\nYour support will be appreciated\nat the November 4th. Election. j\nHarold Salts and John Judson\nof Dundee, spent the week end at\nthe C. L. Laskey home.\nMrs. Adam Blystone, Irvin and\nInez, of Bui key, Ohio, Miss Mar\ngaret' Bucher of Whitehouse, Ohio,\nMrs. Cora Warner and son Eld\nridge Warner, of Liberty Center,\nMr. and Mrs. LaPlante of Toledo,\nwere Sunday dinner guests of A. L.\nLaPlante and family in honor of\nthe birthdays of Mrs. A. L. La\nPlante and Mrs. Warner also the\nwedding anniversary, of Mr. and\nMrs. Vern LaPlante.\nMrs. Mary Finkenbinc\u2019- and fam\nily spent the week end in Toledo.\nMr. and Mrs. Edwin Beightol,\nand family were Sunday dinner\nguests of MY. find Mrs'. George Bai\nghtol. Mr. and Mrs. C. Brown, of\nToledo, were callers in the after\nnoon.\njj -State- jj\nV THEATRE, -NAPOLEON, O\nV FRIDAY and SATURDAY V\ny October 24 25\nX AL JOLHON I.\\ Q\n8 \"BIG Bor x\n8 8\nSI SUNDAY anti MONDAY fk\nOctober 20 27 X\nQ MAURICE CHEVALIER In V\n8\n\nTUESDAY ONLY\n\u201cGRUMPY\u201d\nARIES BEAUTY WARE\nNIGHT\nWEDNESDAY and THURS\nOctober 21) 80\nS\u2019\nfi\n\n\n\u25a03 Ohio Board of Censors j|\njjsooeosoooooei\nNUMBERED MEN\ns\n8\n\n8\nCONRAD NAGEL* BER- Q\nNICE CLAIRE Q\nJust Released by the n\nc\nONCRETE WOR\nDone on Contract,\nUp-to-date mixer,\nand truck. Work\ngauranteed.\nK\nMARK JEFFERS\nPhone 393\nGRAND RAPIDS, OHIO\nBert Snyder ia moving his fam\nily into his mother's home on Main\nStreet.\nMrs. Ellen Hawkins is moving\nher family into the Finkenbiner\nproperty on Second street.\nMr. and Mrs Clarence Freeworth\nMrs. James Bu'rwell, Mrs. Merritt\nSmith and Luette were Napoleon\nshoppers on Tuesday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Schultz cal\nled in Bowling Green, Saturday ev\nening.\nRay Heyman and family of To\nledo and Alva Heyman ana family\nwere Sunday dinner guests of Mr.|\nand Mrs. Lee Heyman.\n\u2014SS-=_^.!_\u2014S>\nHGSHHSHHHHH\nEDW. NYSWANDER\n1 ;v\nPhonograph*\nJewelry and Watch Repairing\nGrand Rapids. Ohio.\nCSHHHHHHISHBl\nIt\u2019s Time For A Change\nA real campaign Is\nunder way In Wood\ncounty this fall, with\nevery indication that\nthere will be a house\ncleaning at the county\nseat.\nRepublicans who\ndare to speak out are\njoining Democrats in\na drive to oust the ma\nchine ring, so long in\ncontrol of county af\nfairs. The cry is go\ning up that it Is time\nfor a change\u2014that po\nlitical trranny and\nJudge Fiesinger\n\u201cWe must change\nthese conditions at\nthe polls. That is the\nonly place to do it.\nWe cannot do our\nbit toward changing\nIt if we return to of\nfice members of tl>^\ncontrolling party in\ncongress. \"Commun\nity loyalty, doesn\u2019t en\nter into the congres\nsional campaign. Nei\nther does friendship.\nMr. Baird is the can\ndidate of a party,\nthat has failed to\nmeet the situ\nrule Dy a suiau aiquc uiuai uc en\nded.\nIThe time has come for a new\ndeal. Argument of the supporters\nof Congressman Baird that he\nshould have a second term is met\nwith the retort that his only con\nspicuous act since his election was\nhis vote for the Hawley-Smoot tar\niff bill, which failed to give far\nmers relief and has keen followed\nby the lowest wheat prices in all\nyears, along with industrial (de\npression, unemployment and the\ncutting of wages. The situation has\nbeen aggravated by the bank fail\nure at the county seat.\n\u201cThe News has always been inde\npendently Democratic, but who\nwould not go Democratic in 1930?\nasks the Wood County News. \u201cWe\nhave been rebuked for daring to\njoke about the raising and lower\ning of the Fiesinger banner. What\ndo you want us to do about it? Cry\n\u201cThe News believes that Mr. Fie\nsinger should be elected to congress\nno matter if Joe Baird is a resident\nof Wood county. Republicans are\nUrging that he be elected because\nof that, not because .he is a Re\npublican. We urge the election of\nM, Fiesinger because he is not a\nRepublican.\n\u201cWe have nothing against Mr.\nBaird personally. We like him. We\nadmire him. But he represents the\nwrong party in congress. His party\nlias achieved nothing\n\u201cIt has bungled the tariff, its dll\nlydallying halted the return of\nprosperity, it forgot its promised\naid to agriculture. The Republican\ncongress hasn\u2019t been much of a\ncongress and Mr. Baird is unfor\ntunate to be a part and parcel of\nsuch a congress.\nanon, a pany uiat nas siumoerea\nat the switch. It must go. He must\ngo with it Loyalty and sentiment\nhare nothing to do with our voting\n\u201cWhen the late Earl Bloom Dem\nocrat, ran for state office, all the\nRepublicans didn\u2019t vote for him,\nbecause of loyalty to his common*\nity. Party politics came first, loypl\nty afterwards. Now they are get\nting sentimental. The shoe is on\nthe other foot. It is a Republican\ncandidate who is cur neighbor. i.\n\u201cSentiment won\u2019t cure the evils\nof the Grundy tariff. Sentimetit\nwon\u2019t help agriculture. Sentiment\nwon\u2019t give the farmer a fair price\nfor his wheat. Sentiment won't\nbring back prosperity. Sentiment\nwon\u2019t give jobs to ithe jobless.\n\u201cWe would like to support Mf.\nI Baird, But we cannot when we\nthink of the Republican record in\ncongress.\n\u201cThere is no reason why anyone\nshould support Mr. Baird, simply\nbecause he lives in Wood county. 1\nWe are electing a congressman, a\nman to represent this district in\nWashington, Do we want to elect\nanother Republican congress and\nget another failure? Did those who\n*hout loyalty vote for Mr. BloomT\n\u201cIt\u2019s different now. The shoe if\non the other foot, and it\u2019s hurting\nRepublican bunions.\u2019\u2019\nJoe Baird has done practically\nnothing all his life, but hold pub-\nlie office, drawing salaries paid by\nthe taxpayers of the county state' J\nor district. Has he any special\nright to continue this for the rest\nof his days?\nIT\u2019S TIME FOI} A CHANGE.\nVOTE FOR JUDGE WM. L. FIE\nSINCER, DEMOCRATIC CANDID-\nATE FOR CONGRESSMAN.\nF1ESINGER-FOR. CONGRESS\nCLUB\nIs on the way\nBetter Hurry to the Bell Store,\nget your underwear, blankets and\npajamas, outing flannels, muslin\nsheets, tubing, hosiery, shoes, rub\nhers, etc., at our BIG ANNIVER\nSARY SALE.\nMyrtle D. King\nGrand Rapids, Ohio\nWill Your Christmas Sav-;\nIngs Check Be Up To Ex\npectations This Year?\nOnly 9 More Weeks Until Xmall\nThe Grand Rapids Banking Co.\nGrand Rapids,\nOhio","height":"29672","width":"21064"}}
